{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565250"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17325"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17325"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.12,0.01,0,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69896"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10015"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"3847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23462"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69896"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of postmenopausal bleeding and vaginal discharge. She underwent total hysterectomy eight years ago for heavy menstrual bleeding. Her medical history includes hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. She is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Speculum examination reveals a 3 cm ulcerated lesion on the upper posterior vaginal wall. There is contact bleeding. No inguinal lymphadenopathy is detected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vaginal squamous cell carcinoma","Vaginal adenocarcinoma","Vaginal sarcoma","Vaginal melanoma","Vaginal intraepithelial neoplasia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with postmenopausal bleeding and an ulcerated vaginal lesion. Given her risk factors (smoking history) and the location of the lesion in the upper third of the vagina, this is most likely primary vaginal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for about 85% of primary vaginal cancers and typically presents in women aged 60-70 years. Risk factors include human papillomavirus infection, smoking, and previous cervical dysplasia. The upper posterior vaginal wall is the most common location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal intraepithelial neoplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a pre-malignant condition that may be asymptomatic or present with discharge. However, it would not typically present as an ulcerated mass with contact bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for about 5-10% of vaginal cancers and is more commonly associated with in-utero diethylstilbestrol exposure, which is not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare tumour that typically presents as a pigmented lesion, although amelanotic variants exist. It tends to occur in the lower third of the vagina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an extremely rare tumour that typically presents in younger women and children. Rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common type in children, while leiomyosarcoma can occur in adults.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary vaginal cancer is rare and most commonly presents with postmenopausal bleeding or discharge.","Most vaginal cancers are squamous cell carcinomas and occur in the upper third of the vagina.","Risk factors for vaginal cancer include HPV infection, smoking, and previous cervical dysplasia."],"references":["Adams TS, Rogers LJ, Cuello MA. Cancer of the vagina: 2021 update. International Journal of Gynecology \u0026 Obstetrics. 2021;155(S1):19\u201327."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17325"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T22:04:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T22:05:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10015"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69896"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes